Mapping Chemical Signatures
The overarching significance of this topic is that it plays a small role in
developing methods for recognizing life on other planets using short range imaging
of chemical signatures. Chemicals can be predictors for life and water, given the
right circumstances. The immediate uses of these research findings will help with
fire mitigation, flood patterns, and other ecological factors. If tracking chemical
signatures can indeed predict the behavior of water over a landscape, then it will
add to scientists’ repertoire of methods for tracking water patterns. Other methods
include topographical maps and measuring drainage units. If scientists can figure
out how chemical signature measurements predict aquatic features, or vice versa,
drawing conclusions about landscapes through imaging technologies will be more
efficient.
Other work has been done to measure
water patterns. Drainage units of
watersheds are measured and categorized
into several classifications, called
Functional Process Zones. These zones
are labeled to describe the behavior of
water, and include meandering,
distributary, braided, pool, and others.
Chemical imaging has also been used to
help facilitate wildlife restoration and
species survival. Programs, such as
ArcGIS, have been developed to assist in
managing the massive quantities of data
produced from chemical imaging.
Our methods for drawing
conclusions based on chemical
signatures will ultimately be k-means
clustering. For the initial state of
analysis, our focus for this topic includes
producing accurate arrays of the
chemical data based on several rasters.
The rasters make up 75 gigabytes of data
and cover over 1600 square miles of land
(not including unused data from outside the boundary). The chemicals being
observed are carbon, carotenoid, cellulose, chlorophyll a & b, d13C isotope, d15N
isotope, fiber, lignin, nitrogen, LMA, NSC, phenolics, phosphorus, and sugar.
Each chemical signature is represented 10 raster files that cover the entirety of the
study area. This data is so large that we needed to use external hard drives to unzip
the main file and only import two chemicals into our local jupyter notebook at one
time.
These rasters were captured by planes flying over the Russian River
Watershed area. So far, we have used two python libraries to cross verify and
compare how the images line up. The goal is to use rioxarray/xarray libraries to
produce an array; however, online sources have made the GDAL library more
accessible for this particular project. Here are three different orderings of nitrogen
rasters.
We have been able to clip the data using both libraries, merge the data into a
large mosaic of all images, and switch orderings of the images to find the correct
map of the area. We have used rioxarray to clip data into a square boundary, and
we have used GDAL to clip the data into a detailed polygon of the area. After
trying several orderings, it does not seem as if we have discovered the correct one.
We have created maps of nitrogen levels and one unclipped map of phosphorus.
We used simple list manipulation to test out different orderings of the ten
nitrogen arrays, which were previously cropped.
The maps clipped with rioxarray look much different from those produced
with GDAL. On the left, we have a map that was clipped using rioxarray and
merged with GDAL. On the right, we have a map that was both clipped and
merged with rioxarray. Both maps were necessary to observe for producing an
accurate mosaic. Our goal is to use rioxarray because we are most familiar with it
and because it will be more efficient to use one library. However we found it
helpful to experiment with GDAL for the time being. Here is the GDAL equivalent
to rxr.clip().
Next, we merged the files using the gdal_merge command.
And finally, we used a function found on neonscience.org.
Once we have discovered the correct order of rasters, we can convert the
mosaic raster into an array and produce a k-means clustering map. Once we have a
clustered map of chemical classifications, we can begin to correspond those
classifications with functional process zones and topographical maps.
Thus far, we have discovered that nitrogen is more highly concentrated on
the north-eastern and south-eastern regions of our study area.
